<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="337" pageId="1" pageNumber="336" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1322,1833,1900]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="337" pageId="1" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,392,1873,1899]" pageId="1" pageNumber="336">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small Heteropodinae (body length 
<quantity box="[844,993,1874,1900]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="4.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="336" unit="mm" value="6.1" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="4.7">4.7–7.5 mm</quantity>
) without lateral spines on metatarsi I­II. Male cymbium retrobasally with bent spur, embolus with loop running transversally to plane of alveolus. Females with spirally coiled copulatory openings similar to those in 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon 1880" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1880" box="[485,778,364,390]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Spariolenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[485,625,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Spariolenus</emphasis>
Simon 
<number box="[717,778,364,390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1880.0">1880</number>
</taxonomicName>
, differing from the latter in having a pit in the posterior part of the median septum. Internal duct system with broad lateral loops and subsequent narrow ducts, the latter running parallel or slightly converging close to the median line.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="337" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,452,523,549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name is a word consisting of the family name of Prof. Dr Jochen Martens and the last part of the genus name 
<taxonomicName box="[868,1007,564,589]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Heteropoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[868,1007,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Heteropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; it is feminine in gender. It pays tribute to Prof. Martens and his scientific contributions to the Arachnology and the zoogeography of Asian mountain ranges (especially Himalaya). Moreover, I express my personal thanks towards Prof. Martens for supervising and guiding me in my first years of taxonomic and systematic research.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="338" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,463,764,790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Description.</emphasis>
Male cymbium with prolateral bulge (PB), giving a unique general appearance (
<figureCitation box="[411,517,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 2, 5</figureCitation>
). Embolus with filiform apophysis, the latter arising on the ventrally bent part of the embolus (
<figureCitation box="[577,651,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number box="[634,651,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tip of embolic apophysis serrated (
<figureCitation box="[1101,1175,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number box="[1158,1175,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Conductor strongly reduced (C in 
<figureCitation box="[540,612,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number box="[595,612,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Subtegulum visible in prolateral half of bulb (
<figureCitation box="[1183,1253,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number box="[1239,1253,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); this fact and the extraordinary conformation of the embolus resulting from a rotation of the whole bulb of about 
<number box="[515,547,964,990]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="90.0">90</number>
° in a retrolateral direction (ventrally). RTA long and not divided into two parts as in other genera of Heteropodinae, its tip widened in retrolateral view (
<figureCitation box="[272,379,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Figs 
<number box="[331,379,1044,1070]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Female epiygne with anteriorly and posteriorly diverging septum and posterior median pocket (PP in 
<figureCitation box="[550,628,1084,1110]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[289,1303,318,1091]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[289,1304,318,1092]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (9 – 10, 12 PJ 1772, 11 PJ 1775). 9, 11 Epigyne, ventral; 10 Internal duct system, dorsal; 12 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal. LL lateral loops of internal duct system, MS median septum, PA pit anterior to septum, PP pit posterior to septum, R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174022/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number box="[611,628,1084,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Epigynal field roundish to transversally oval, without anterior bands (
<figureCitation box="[458,540,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[289,1303,318,1091]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[289,1304,318,1092]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (9 – 10, 12 PJ 1772, 11 PJ 1775). 9, 11 Epigyne, ventral; 10 Internal duct system, dorsal; 12 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal. LL lateral loops of internal duct system, MS median septum, PA pit anterior to septum, PP pit posterior to septum, R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174022/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[558,590,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 21" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 21. Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (13 – 16 PJ 1776, 17 PJ 1777, 18 – 19 lectotype PJ 1705, 21 – 21 paralectotype PJ 1706). 13, 17 – 18, 20 Epigyne, ventral; 14 – 15 Internal duct system, dorsal (15 right half partly broken and shifted); 16 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal; 19, 21 Left chelicera, showing dentition, ventral. R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174023/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">13</figureCitation>
). Internal duct system with a lateral coil similar to that in 
<taxonomicName box="[264,381,1164,1189]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Barylestis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,381,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Barylestis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. One part of the duct system, functionally situated behind the first windings and the fertilisation ducts, running parallel along the median line (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1130,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[289,1303,318,1091]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[289,1304,318,1092]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (9 – 10, 12 PJ 1772, 11 PJ 1775). 9, 11 Epigyne, ventral; 10 Internal duct system, dorsal; 12 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal. LL lateral loops of internal duct system, MS median septum, PA pit anterior to septum, PP pit posterior to septum, R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174022/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1142,1219,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 21" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 21. Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (13 – 16 PJ 1776, 17 PJ 1777, 18 – 19 lectotype PJ 1705, 21 – 21 paralectotype PJ 1706). 13, 17 – 18, 20 Epigyne, ventral; 14 – 15 Internal duct system, dorsal (15 right half partly broken and shifted); 16 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal; 19, 21 Left chelicera, showing dentition, ventral. R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174023/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
14– 
<number box="[1190,1219,1204,1230]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Eye size ratios typical for Heteropodinae: lateral larger than median eyes, particular posterior eyes only slightly larger than anterior eyes. DS length / DS width = 
<number box="[1221,1258,1284,1310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.1">1.1</number>
(1.0, n= 
<number box="[302,313,1324,1350]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.0">1</number>
); DS width / anterior width of DS = 
<number box="[743,836,1324,1350]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.7999999999999998" valueMax="1.9" valueMin="1.7">1.7–1.9</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Cheliceral teeth variable: basic pattern for Heteropodinae 
<number box="[995,1010,1364,1390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="3.0">3</number>
anterior, 
<number box="[1123,1137,1364,1390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="4.0">4</number>
posterior teeth; 
<taxonomicName box="[264,435,1404,1429]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Martensopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[264,435,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Martensopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[443,554,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[443,554,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
: 
<number box="[570,614,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
anterior, 
<number box="[728,772,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5</number>
posterior teeth (
<figureCitation box="[965,1103,1404,1430]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 21" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 21. Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (13 – 16 PJ 1776, 17 PJ 1777, 18 – 19 lectotype PJ 1705, 21 – 21 paralectotype PJ 1706). 13, 17 – 18, 20 Epigyne, ventral; 14 – 15 Internal duct system, dorsal (15 right half partly broken and shifted); 16 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal; 19, 21 Left chelicera, showing dentition, ventral. R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174023/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 19, 21</figureCitation>
). Posterior margin of chelicerae between teeth and fang with one long curved bristle, apparently typical within Heteropodinae (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Levy" box="[573,704,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="345" refString="Levy, G. (1989) The family of huntsman spiders in Israel with annotations on spiders of the Middle East (Araneae: Sparassidae). Journal of Zoology, 217, 127 - 176." type="journal article" year="1989">
Levy 
<number box="[641,704,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 
<number box="[763,811,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="130.0">130</number>
). Female palpus claw with 
<number box="[1131,1175,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
teeth; shape of palpal and leg claw typical for Heteropodinae (
<figureCitation box="[857,995,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1079,1103]" captionTargetBox="[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (22 – 23 PJ 1776, 24 – 25 PJ 1778). 26 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., Ψ paratype from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (PJ 1772). 22 Claw of right pedipalpus, retrolateral; 23 Prolateral claw of right leg I, prolateral; 24, 26 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal; 25 Sternum, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174024/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Figs 
<number box="[917,995,1524,1550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="22.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="22.0">22–23</number>
</figureCitation>
). Leg length pattern (
<number box="[1251,1312,1524,1550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2413.0">2413</number>
) fits scheme found by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jager" box="[526,675,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="345" refString="Jager, P. (2001) Diversitat der Riesenkrabbenspinnen im Himalaya. Uber eine Radiation zweier Gattungen in den Schneetropen. (Araneae: Sparassidae: Heteropodinae). Courier Forshungsinstitut Senckenberg, 232, 1 - 136." type="journal article" year="2001">
Jäger (
<number box="[605,666,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for other Heteropodinae (
<number box="[988,1048,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2413.0">2413</number>
for specimens &lt;
<quantity box="[1260,1320,1564,1590]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
DS length, 
<number box="[395,454,1604,1630]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2143.0">2143</number>
&gt; 
<quantity box="[476,537,1604,1630]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
DS length). Legs showing general trend for reducing spines: femur (retrolateral), tibiae I–II (prolateral), tibiae IV (retrolateral). Patella spination variable: 000–001. Metatarsus III additionally to metatarsus IV with additional distal median ventral spine; metatarsus III variable: 2014, 2024, 
<number box="[873,935,1724,1750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2025.0">2025</number>
. Trochanters with ventral notch. Trilobate membrane with median hook and lateral projection of similar size (
<figureCitation box="[1168,1239,1764,1790]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number box="[1222,1239,1764,1790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" lastBlockId="3.[264,1323,284,950]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="338" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Generally light coloured to pale spiders. Dorsal shield of prosoma and sternum with dark, partly faint markings, eyes with distinct dark patches (
<figureCitation box="[1000,1079,1844,1870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1096,1175,1844,1870]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25" captionStart-1="FIGURES 27 – 30. 27 – 28" captionStartId-0="8.[264,382,1079,1103]" captionStartId-1="9.[264,382,1344,1368]" captionTargetBox-0="[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetBox-1="[276,1309,486,1318]" captionTargetId-0="figure@8.[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetId-1="figure@9.[276,1310,486,1318]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="9" captionText-0="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (22 – 23 PJ 1776, 24 – 25 PJ 1778). 26 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., Ψ paratype from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (PJ 1772). 22 Claw of right pedipalpus, retrolateral; 23 Prolateral claw of right leg I, prolateral; 24, 26 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal; 25 Sternum, ventral." captionText-1="FIGURES 27 – 30. 27 – 28 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype, ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India. 29 – 30 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (27, 29 dorsal aspect; 28, 30 ventral aspect). See illustrations for identification (PJ) number." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/174024/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/174025/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
24– 
<number box="[1144,1175,1844,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="30.0">30</number>
</figureCitation>
). Chelicerae with longitudinal stripes typical for Heteropodinae (
<figureCitation box="[873,948,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[961,1038,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1079,1103]" captionTargetBox="[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (22 – 23 PJ 1776, 24 – 25 PJ 1778). 26 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., Ψ paratype from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (PJ 1772). 22 Claw of right pedipalpus, retrolateral; 23 Prolateral claw of right leg I, prolateral; 24, 26 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal; 25 Sternum, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174024/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
24, 
<number box="[1005,1038,284,310]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="338" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,284,950]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,472,323,349]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from South 
<collectingCountry box="[788,849,324,350]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">India</collectingCountry>
(Tamil Nadu State: Palni Hills; Kerala State: Cardamon Hills).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,284,950]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,536,403,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Species included.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[553,866,404,429]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Martensopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transversa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[553,866,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Martensopoda transversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[884,988,403,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[884,988,403,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Reimoser 1934" authorityName="Reimoser" authorityYear="1934" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Martensopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuscula" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1013,1323,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Martensopoda minuscula</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Reimoser" box="[272,453,444,470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="345" refString="Reimoser, E. (1934) Araneae aus Sud-Indien. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 41, 465 - 511." type="journal article" year="1934">
Reimoser 
<number box="[393,453,444,470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" value="1934.0">1934</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[469,599,444,470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="338" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,284,950]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,488,483,509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Relationships.</emphasis>
Although some resemblance with the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1105,1245,484,509]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Spariolenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1105,1245,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Spariolenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[379,439,524,550]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[500,572,524,550]" name="Oman" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Oman</collectingCountry>
exists, i.e., male conductor reduced, spirally coiled copulatory openings and median septum not clearly recognisable (fused?) in females, a sister relationship cannot be proposed unambiguously. From the copulatory organs, especially of the male, it seems that copulation posture and mechanics should be clearly different from the basic pattern in the subfamily. This concerns the use of the unique cymbial spur but also the transversally oriented embolus loop. This singularity justifies in my opinion the erection of a new genus. Considering the small size of the two known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,435,804,829]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Martensopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[264,435,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Martensopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[450,566,804,830]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[450,566,804,830]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the mountainous habitats, where they were found, and the overall high diversity of soil living arthropods in such habitats, it might be worth searching in similar regions for further undescribed and potential sister taxa of 
<taxonomicName box="[1091,1262,884,909]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Martensopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1091,1262,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Martensopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" pageNumber="338" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
